🧠 What is a Callback Function?

A **callback function** is a function that is **passed as an argument to another function** and is executed later.

Example idea:

```text
Function → Performs task → Calls callback
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Simple Callback Example

```javascript
function greet(name, callback) {
  console.log("Hello " + name);
  callback();
}

function sayBye() {
  console.log("Goodbye!");
}

greet("Saakshi", sayBye);
```

Output:

```text
Hello Saakshi
Goodbye!
```

Explanation:

1️⃣ greet function runs
2️⃣ callback function executes after

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Why Node.js Uses Callbacks

Node.js is **asynchronous and non-blocking**.

Callbacks allow:

✔ Efficient I/O operations
✔ Handling tasks after completion
✔ Running multiple operations simultaneously

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Callback in File Reading

Example using `fs` module:

```javascript
const fs = require("fs");

fs.readFile("file.txt", "utf8", (err, data) => {

  if (err) {
    console.error(err);
    return;
  }

  console.log(data);
});
```

Explanation:

1️⃣ File reading starts
2️⃣ Node continues executing other code
3️⃣ Callback runs when file reading finishes

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Callback Flow in Node.js

Execution flow:

```text
Start Task → Continue Program → Task Finished → Callback Executes
```

This keeps the **event loop free**.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Example with Timeout

```javascript
console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Callback executed");
}, 2000);

console.log("End");
```

Output:

```text
Start
End
Callback executed
```

Explanation:

Node.js does **not wait** for the timeout.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Error-First Callback Pattern

Node.js follows a standard callback pattern:

```javascript
function callback(error, result) {
}
```

Example:

```javascript
fs.readFile("file.txt", (err, data) => {

  if (err) {
    console.log("Error:", err);
    return;
  }

  console.log(data);
});
```

Rule:

```text
First parameter → error
Second parameter → result
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Callback Hell

When callbacks are nested too deeply, code becomes hard to read.

Example:

```javascript
fs.readFile("file1.txt", (err, data1) => {

  fs.readFile("file2.txt", (err, data2) => {

    fs.readFile("file3.txt", (err, data3) => {

      console.log(data1, data2, data3);

    });

  });

});
```

This is called **Callback Hell**.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Problems with Callback Hell

❌ Hard to read
❌ Hard to debug
❌ Difficult error handling
❌ Deep nesting

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Solutions to Callback Hell

Modern JavaScript provides better solutions.

1️⃣ Promises
2️⃣ Async/Await

Example with Promise:

```javascript
fs.promises.readFile("file.txt", "utf8")
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
```

Example with async/await:

```javascript
async function readFile() {
  const data = await fs.promises.readFile("file.txt", "utf8");
  console.log(data);
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Callback vs Promise vs Async/Await

| Feature        | Callback  | Promise | Async/Await |
| -------------- | --------- | ------- | ----------- |
| Syntax         | Complex   | Better  | Clean       |
| Error Handling | Difficult | Easier  | Very easy   |
| Readability    | Poor      | Good    | Best        |

